## IMPROVEMENT 2 — LAYER PARENTING

### 2.1 The problem

If a scene has 5 layers with staggered timing and the user
wants to delay the whole group by 2 seconds, they currently
have to update each layer's startAt individually.
Layer parenting solves this: delay the parent, all children shift.

### 2.2 Data model changes

```ts
interface BaseLayer {
  // ... existing fields ...
  parentLayerId: string | null  // NEW — null = root layer
  // startAt is relative to parent's startAt if parentLayerId is set
  // absolute startAt = parent.absoluteStartAt + this.startAt
}
```

Add a computed property (not stored, derived):
```ts
function getAbsoluteStartAt(
  layer: SceneLayer,
  allLayers: SceneLayer[]
): number {
  if (!layer.parentLayerId) return layer.startAt;
  const parent = allLayers.find(l => l.id === layer.parentLayerId);
  if (!parent) return layer.startAt;
  return getAbsoluteStartAt(parent, allLayers) + layer.startAt;
}
```

### 2.3 Parent-child relationships

Rules:
- A layer can have at most one parent
- Parents cannot be children of their own children (no cycles)
- Deleting a parent: children become root layers (startAt
  becomes their previous absolute startAt)
- Hiding a parent: hides all children (CSS visibility on layer div)
- A parent layer can itself be invisible (opacity: 0) —
  it exists only for timing/grouping, not rendering

